.edu/news/articles/2023/06/study-finds-eye-gaze-signals-provide-key-answers-in-assistive-device-control/index.html"><img alt="Eye gaze signal study" class="image-block lazyload" src="https://www.mccormick.northwestern.edu/images/news/2023/06/study-finds-eye-gaze-signals-provide-key-answers-in-assistive-device-control-tn.jpg"/></a></div><div class="feature-content"><h4 class="alternate feature-title"><a class="" href="https://www.mccormick.northwestern.edu/news/articles/2023/06/study-finds-eye-gaze-signals-provide-key-answers-in-assistive-device-control/index.html" target="">Study Finds Eye Gaze Signals Provide Key Answers in Assistive Device Control</a></h4><p class="feature-copy">Researchers with Northwestern's Center for Advancing Safety of Machine Intelligence (CASMI) used eye-tracking technology to gather eye gaze signal data, and concluded that it’s likely that assistive devices can be designed to allow for smoother control. </p></div></article></section></section></aside>
                    
                    
